{"/service/ndnp/ncu/batch_ncu_chestnut_ver01/data/sn91068748/00415667401/1921012801/0515.xml":{"full_text":"FUIUSHID EVESY ftJDAT BY\nTie Herald Publishing Co., Inc.\nJ. T. Stainback\nF. M. Shuts\nEditob\nManager\nSaWripti 12.09 a Tear ia Advaace\nTELEPHONE S70\nFntarad aa Second Claaa Matter April\n8, a914, at the Poet Office at Roanoka\nRapida, North Caroline, under Act of\nMarch 8. 1879.\nAll commonlcatfone ehould be\naddreeaed to the Herald Publishing Co.\nPereona wlehing return of maa, mint in\nall raaee enclose atampa.\ndefectives, in restoring to\nthose who have \"gone wrong\"\nbetter ideals of life and conduct\nand citizenship is again worth\nevery cent it has cost us.\nWe believe that the Public\nWelfare work has come to stay;\nthat as soon as what is being\naccomplished is mor widely\nknown and its purpose more\ngenerally understood, it will be\nso widened and strengthen as to\ncover fully the duty of society to\nits children and its unfortunates.\nThe Extreme Of\nCynical Impudence\nan nf thanki. resolutions of re\nwill be chanted for at\nthe rate of ten cents per line, casn\nmust accompany article in all cases ei\ncept here customer has a regular ac\ncount No Insertions made for less\nban 26 centa.\nFriday. January 28,1921\nWarren is showing no indica\ntions of speed as a Cabinet\nMaker.\nMr. Harding must have gotten\na sufficiency of consultation with\nbest minds.\nRosemary has a lesson and\nwarning.in the disastrous fire of\nlast Tuesday afternoon.\nMr. Penrose seems to be labor\ning under a misapprehension as\nto who really is President-elect.\nWe think the most of us can\nbear up pretty well under the\nlost of those forty eight addition\nal congressmen.\nConsider the hard case of Char\nley Schwab whose expenses for\none month reached the amazing\nfigure of $260,000.00\nA sane planting program this\nanrincrwill do more than any\nthing else to steady prices and\nhasten the return of prosperity\n\"Some are born crazy, some\nachieve craziness and some have\nincome tax blanks thrust upon\nthem\" wails the Nashville Ten\nnessean.\nThe Norlina affair strikes us a\ndenlorable but necessary mci\ndent If a set of blacks ever\nneeded an object lesson in white\nsunremacy it was those Warren\ncounty negroes.\nPublic Welfare\nElsewhere on this page is\nprinted a letter from the Direct\nor of Public Welfare at Chape\nHill to Mr. R. D. Jenkins, Coun\ntv Suoerintendent of Public Wei\nfare for Halifax County. In\nview of the fact that the office\nof the County Superintendent of\nPublic Welfare has been under\nfire in this county, it is interest-\nins to note the favorable im\npression Mr. Jenkin's work is\nmakinz in hieh circles.\nProbably no phase of county\ngovernmental activity is less\nfamiliar to the average citizen\nthan the work of the Health Offi\ncer and the Suoerintendent o\nPublic Welfare, due to the fact\nthat here government is break\ning new pound. Enlightened\npublic opinion forced the legisla\nture of North Carolina last year\nto recoflmize the leeal duty o;\norganized society not only to re\nstrain but to sustain and care for\nmoral and mental defectives and\nto enforce the right of every\nNorth Carolina child to at least\na grammar school education.\nThe School attendance alone\nin North Carolina was 'increased\nthrough the Public Welfare work\nby more than one hundred thous\nand and the average daily at\ntendance was increased by\neighty seven thousand. This\nalone ia worth in the added ef\nfectiveness of our educations\nplant more than the Publie We\nfire work has cost us. The\nbenefit! of education to those\nchildren who would otherwise\nnot bare received it are incal\nculablehuman happiness and\nDrosresj an not be expressed in\ndollars and cents.\nMuch more has been done.\nThe work of the Superintendents\nof Public Welfare in restraining\nwayward boys and girls, in alle\ntfitiag the distress of mental\nEX TRAVIS. R. E L. TRAVIS, .R.\nTRAVIS TRAVIS\nAttorneys at Law\nHALIFAX. N. C\nPractice in the State and Federal Courts\nAllen C Zollicoffer\nAttorney at Law\nRosemary, N. C\nOffice Orer OU Postofflee BuMng\nW. C. WILLIAMS\nLicensed Embalmer and Undertaker\nPrompt Satisfactory Service\nDay Phone 633; Night Phone 589-3\nThe Neal bill for the redisrict\ning of the state for the state\nsenate is as cynically imprudent\na violation of every principle or\ndemocratic government as was\never offered a state. The pro\nponents of this measure have evi-\nr\ndently come to the conclusion\nthat the time has arrived when\nia safe in North Carolina to\ndrop the last pretence of regard\n'or justice and honesty m state\naffairs, and to proceed boldly\nand shamelessly to the perpetra\ntion of whatever iniquity appears\nlikely to benefit their party.\nThe most superficial examina\ntion reveals the rottenness of thv-\nnroDosal. Examine the following\nfigures, taken at random:\nThird district, Bertie ana\nNorthampton, two senators. To\ntal population. 47,177, One sen\nator to 23,589 people, boiidiy\nDemocratic.\nThirtv-third district, Cherokee,\nClay, Graham, Macon and Swain,\none senator. Total population,\n50, 871. One senator to more than\ntwice as many people as in the\nthird. Solidly Republican.\nSixth district, Pitt county, one\nsenator. Population, 45,5vy.\nSolidly Democratic.\nSeventeenth district, Guilford\nand Rockingham, two senators.\nTotal DODulation. 123.421. One\nsenator to 61,211 people-nearly\nthree times as many as in the\ntlard. Democratic, but none too\nSf'lid.\nTwenty-second district, For-\nsjth county, one senator. Popu\nlation, 77,269 a constituency\nrr.ore than three times as large\nas that represented by each sen\nator from the third. Democratic\nat present, but exhibiting a dis\ntressing tendency to vote for A.\nE. Holton now and then.\nSo it goes. The bill is a bare\nfaced attempt to rob the west of\niU representation in the state\nsc-nate because, forsooth, the\nwest does not furnish ardent\nenough support to suit the dicta\nte rs down in Raleigh.\nHas the Democratic party real\nly grown so weak in North Caro\nlina that it is necessary to tighten\nits grip on power by such an out-\nn ee as this? The passage of\nthis bill would be tantamount to\nan admission on the part of the\nmajority that it dare not trust to\nthe decision of the people. It\nwould be a fatal admission, but\nif Democracy is going to intrust\nits leadership to the hands of the\nBourbons, with A. D. Watts in\nthe lead, then it is certain to be\nbetrayed sooner or later into\nfatal admission. Greensboro\nDaily News.\nGLOVER SMITH\nFURNITURE and UNDERTAKING\nLICENSED EMBALMER\nRoanoke Rapids,\nDay Phone 506\nN.C.\nNight Phone 540\np\nIff\ni\nOn Hand and Made\nTo Order\nTrusses, Abdominal Supporters, Elastic\nStockings, Artificial Limbs, Crutches, Canes,\nInvalid Chairs, Braces, Etc.\np\n9.\nP\nr APTIFlOl UVPS\nCORRESPONDENCE\nSOLICITED\nAMobum! Supvorlan\nThwt niprotttn ar utcd in corpulency, kerni. ni ill tbckaiul compUhrt\nin men 01 wimtn. 1 1 ty ie lucron where needed inott.\nKEEP THIS IT li L NOT PPFAR ACA1N\nPENTZ TOWER\n310 Cilr Hall Ay.du. Norfolk. V..\nI-\"J\ni\ni\ni\nu\nA. L CLARK\nLIFE AND FIRE\nINSURANCE\nLoans Negotiated on Real\nEstate\ni v martin\nGanrabar. N. 0.\nSauokBpMi.M.C\nft. A. MATTWWf. ekBatf M. C.\nMASON, LONG S MlflEWS\nAttorneys at Law\nOffice Roanoke Rapti N. C, end\nJackaoa, N. C\nRoanoke Rapids Power Company\nRoanoke Rapids. N. C.\nSave Your Money by Buying a Building Lot on\nEASY PAYMENTS\nElectrical Power for all Purposes at Low Rates\nState and County\nTaxes Now Due\nYour 1920 State and County\nTaxes are now due. A dit\ncount of I is allowable I 4\nthe tune are paid before Dec\nember I, 1920.\nFor the month of December\nthey are nek\nAfter January I, 1921, inter\neft at the rate of 1 pet\nmonth will be charged,\nPay your taxes promptly and\nsave money.\nH L. BELL\nRosemary, N.C\nTat CtJWctw tar Hiiiki laaies TtvMaia\nApproves Public Welfare\nWork\n(Copy)\nOffice of the Director.\nChapel Hill, N. C.\nJan. 22. 1921\nMr. R. D. Jenkins,\nDepartment of Public Welfare,\nRosemary, N. C.\nMv dear Mr. Jenkins,\nMay I keep your report for\nour file here or do you need this\necov for your own use? I am de\nlighted to look through its pages\nand to know the fine work which\nyou are doing. In looking over\nit hurriedly, as I must this morn\ninz. I have nothing to criticise,\nand it seems to me that you have\ndone work, which, if it were\nknown throughout the State,\nwould carrv conviction as to\nPublic Welfare. I shall be glad\nto write you definitely if there\nare anv suggestions to make\nafter I have looked it over care\nfully. I wish I had a report\nline this from every county.\nCordially Yours,\nHoward W. Odum,\nDirector.\nThe University of North Caro\nlina School of Public Welfare,\nChapal Hill.\nWhite Star Laundry\n.Phone 218\nWeldon, N. C.\nEffective Monday, January 31st, our truck\nwill make calls in Rosemary and Roanoke\nRapids on Mondays and Wednesdays in\nstead of Tuesdays and Wednesdays as\nheretofore.\nOur truck will call anywhere and any time\non the above days specified. Your pack\nages may be left with any of our agents\nnamed below.\nNote Our Reductions on Shirts\nDress Shirts 15c Work Shirts 12c\nAgents\nMatkin's Barber Shop, Roanoke Rapids\nTickel Barber Shop. Rosemary\nRosemary Barber Shop. Rosemary\nWhite Star Laundry\nWeldon, N. C.\nRemoval Notice\nWe extend a hearty invitation to visit us in our new location\nCitizens Bank Building\nRosemary, N. C.\nAt this time, the beginning of our Ninth year of business,\nwe heartily thank our friends for the generous patronage\ngiven us and respectfully solicit a continuance of the con\nfidence reposed in us.\nWe shall endeavor to deserve a large share of your or\nders by supplying the latest Novelties and Styles at all\ntimes and rendering a service unsurpassed.\nMiss Annie Wedlin\nRosemary, N. C.\nSend us your inquiries for\nLUMBER\nFLOORING\nSIDING\nFRAMING\nWINDOWS\nDOORS\nBEAVER BOARD\nPAINTS\nROOFING\nand other building material\nWe will give you high grade stock\nand prompt and efficient service\nL E. Wollett Son\nLITTLETON, ft C\naawtf\nLincoln Said:\nintend no modification of my\noft expressed wish that all men\neverywhere should be free.'\nThis Statement of the great emancipator might well\nbe applied to individuals. Are you one of those\nwho enjoy financial freedom? If not, we can show\nyou many ways to attain it.\nFirst of all, by practicing a little thrift each week\nand laying aside a few spare dollars in a savings\naccount with us, will Start you on the road to finan\ncial independence, we help you by adding 4 per\ncent interest.\n4 Per Cent Interest on Savings\nThe First National Bank\nof Roanoke Rapids\nMember of the Federal Reserve Syttem\nCAWYCHF,Pieit\nS. F. PATTtRSON, V-Prat\nj.T.STAiNBACK,Caihier\nT.W,MlXNG,V.Pieii.","height":"28296","width":"19288"}}
